	directAnswerHtml={`<strong style="color: var(--color-ink);">If you are a Buddhist exploring the Bible, you are welcome here — and you are deeply respected.</strong> The Buddhist tradition holds profound wisdom: the honest reckoning with suffering (dukkha), the practice of compassion (karuna), the discipline of mindfulness, and the courage to seek an end to pain through stillness and effort. The <a href="https://fathersheartbible.com/read" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Father's Heart Bible™</a> is a fresh English translation you can read and <em>listen to</em> free — and it reveals God not as a distant force but as a <em>Father</em>. Whether you have searched "is there a God who loves me," "Bible verses about suffering and peace," "who is God in the Bible," or "rest for the weary," the heart of it is gentle and simple: you do not have to strive your way to peace alone. There is a Father who meets you in your suffering and offers you rest.`}
	keyTakeaway={`You are not alone in your suffering, and you do not have to earn your way to peace through effort alone — there is a personal Father who meets you in your pain and gives you rest.`}
	painsHeading={`Buddhists around the world`}
	painsIntroHtml={`Across the world, hundreds of millions of people walk the Buddhist path with sincerity and discipline — seeking to understand suffering, to cultivate compassion, and to find peace. These are not statistics about strangers; they are a window into a deeply human longing many of us share.`}
