	painsBodyHtml={`<p>At the heart of the Buddhist path is an honest truth that few traditions face so directly: life holds real suffering, and pretending otherwise helps no one. There is genuine wisdom and courage in that clear-eyed reckoning — and in the patient practice of compassion, mindfulness, and discipline that follows from it. Many who walk this path carry a deep and sincere longing for peace, and they pursue it faithfully through their own effort, stillness, and detachment.</p><p>And yet, in the quiet, many also feel the weight of striving alone. To seek an end to suffering largely by one's own discipline is a heavy and solitary road. What if peace did not have to be earned entirely on your own? What if, in the very midst of suffering, there were Someone who knew you, loved you, and came near — not a distant force, but a Father who offers rest? This is not a claim to argue against the path you know; it is a gentle invitation to consider a love that meets you on it.</p>`}
	painsSources={[
		{ label: `Pew Research — The Global Religious Landscape (Buddhists)`, url: `https://www.pewresearch.org/religion/2012/12/18/global-religious-landscape-buddhist/` },
