	voicesCreditHtml={`Photos via <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="color: var(--color-brand);" class="hover:underline">Wikimedia Commons</a> &mdash; George MacDonald, Charles Spurgeon, and Andrew Murray (all public domain).`}
	wordHeading={`His Word will not return void`}
	wordBodyHtml={`<p>You may not feel anything the first time you read. That is alright. The Father is patient, and He is in no hurry with you. He does not ask you to arrive at peace through striving — only to come, and to let His words settle quietly in you, like rain on dry ground.</p><p class="mt-4" style="color: var(--color-ink);">"My word… will not return to me empty, but will accomplish that which I purpose." <span style="color: var(--color-muted);">— Isaiah 55:11</span></p>`}
	fatherSaysHeading={`What your Father says over you`}
	fatherSaysHtml={`<p>"I have seen the suffering you have faced so honestly, and the long road you have walked seeking peace. You do not have to carry it alone any longer. I am not far from you. Come to Me — just as you are, weary and burdened — and I will give you rest.</p><p>You do not have to climb to Me by your own effort. I came near to you first, because I love you. You are not a lone seeker to Me; you are My child. Lay the weight down. Let Me quiet your heart with My love, and let Me be the Father who walks with you the rest of the way."</p>`}
	prayerHeading={`A prayer for Buddhists`}
	prayerHtml={`<p>Our Father, we lift up to You every person walking the Buddhist path — the millions who have faced suffering with honesty, who practice compassion, and who seek peace with sincere and patient hearts. We thank You for the wisdom and the longing You have placed within them.</p><p>Father, would You meet them in the very suffering they have faced so bravely. Where the path has felt solitary, let them sense that they are not alone. Where they have striven for peace, let them encounter the peace that comes only as Your gift. Draw near to the brokenhearted among them, and quiet their hearts with Your love.</p><p>Reveal Yourself to them not as a distant force, but as a Father who knows them by name and delights in them. Let them taste the rest You offer to all who are weary. Guard them, comfort them, and lead them gently into the embrace of Your love.</p><p>In Jesus' name, amen.</p>`}
