	faqs={[
		{ question: `Is there a God who loves me personally?`, answer: `The Bible's answer is yes — not a distant force, but a personal Father who knows you by name. 1 John 3:1 speaks of the great love the Father has given, that we should be called His children, and Psalm 34:18 says He is near to the brokenhearted. In the Father's Heart Bible™ you meet God as a Father who comes near to you in your suffering. Read and hear these free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `What does the Bible say about suffering?`, answer: `Scripture faces suffering honestly rather than denying it. John 16:33 says plainly that in this world you will face trouble — yet it offers peace in the midst of it. Matthew 11:28 invites the weary and burdened to come and find rest, and Psalm 34:18 says God draws near to the crushed in spirit. The Father's Heart Bible™ reveals a Father who meets you in suffering rather than leaving you to bear it alone. Read it free, with audio, at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Who is God in the Bible — a force or a person?`, answer: `The Bible reveals God as personal — and tenderly, as a Father. Romans 8:15 says we can cry out 'Abba, Father,' and Matthew 6:26 describes a heavenly Father who cares for you because you are precious to Him. The Father's Heart Bible™ is the first English translation to reveal God as Father wherever Scripture does, so you meet Someone who knows and loves you. Read it free at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
		{ question: `Does the Bible offer rest for the weary?`, answer: `Yes — directly. Matthew 11:28 records Jesus saying, 'Come to Me, all who are weary and carrying heavy burdens, and I will give you rest.' This rest is offered as a gift, not earned through striving. John 14:27 adds the promise of a peace the world cannot give. You can read and listen to these passages free in the Father's Heart Bible™ at fathersheartbible.com/read.` },
